We recommended that:
Management stops the practice of procurement of meals and snacks thru emergency purchase for the scheduled seminars, trainings, and/or activities of the LGU;
Management ensures that all procurement shall be meticulously planned to warrant that the most advantageous price for the government is obtained;
Management requires the BAC to strategize their procurement activities, ensuring that the implementation of projects or programs are met, for operational efficiency and cost-effectiveness in compliance with Section 7 of the IRR of RA 9184; and
The BAC Chairwoman commented that said procurements may have been a response to urgent situations however, the BAC were aware that it is indispensable to recognize the lapses as emergency purchases should not be used as workaround for standard procurement process. Nonetheless, the BAC committed to comply with the audit recommendations.

We recommended that Management to require all barangays to immediately cause the Liquidation of all funds transferred to them from CY 2018-2022.  Otherwise, the LGU should not grant additional funds to barangays unless all fund transfers were already liquidated;

Monitor the projects implemented by the barangays and the compliance of the projects to the above-mentioned JMC; and

Henceforth, all projects transferred to the barangays should be identified specifically in the MOA. Also, all barangay resolutions should be supported by Approved Program of Work (for Infrastructure Projects) and Approved Project Expenditures or Estimated Expenses indicating project objective and expected output (for other projects)

We commended the Management’s efforts in the liquidation CA granted for the current year. However, we still reiterated our recommendations that management requires the Municipal Accountant to:
continue the issuance of demand letters to notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances. If settlement was not received, withhold the corresponding amount from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate;
not grant additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advance granted them have been liquidated;
strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and
strictly comply with the provisions of the abovementioned Circular.

Based on the foregoing circumstances, we reiterated our recommendations that management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to update, reconcile and revisit the balances reported with the source agency immediately and draw adjusting entries as necessary;
Require the concerned Accountable Officer/s to review the implementation of the same and cause the liquidation thereof;
Return to the Source Agency any unused/unutilized balance relating to the fund transfers; and
Explain the cause of delayed liquidation of fund transfers.

We recommended that management:
Submit the documentary requirements to support the grant of BAC Honoraria;
Compute, withhold and remit the withholding tax applicable to the members of the BAC;
Explain the charging of inappropriate expenditures from the proceeds of the sale of bidding documents and explain why should it not be disallowed in audit; and
Comply to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-001, BIR Revenue Regulations No. 11-2018 and the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

Review all Supplemental budgets passed by the SB members to determine the total cash that could have been transferred from economic enterprise bank accounts to general fund account;
Review all payrolls of employees of economic enterprises from CY 2015 to March 2019 to determine the total amount of remitted mandatory obligations that was withdrawn from the general fund account instead of the proper economic enterprises bank account; and
Thereafter, to make appropriate adjustments to correct the abnormal balances to come up and report fairly presented financial statements.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Mayor appoint/authorize a permanent employee to be the Petty Cash Custodian of the Municipality;
Thereafter, the designated Petty Cash Custodian should be properly bonded;
The PCC must ensure that the required documentary requirements for each transaction charged to the PC are properly prepared, approved and attached to the claim to improve the transparency on the utilization of the funds; and
The PC should not be used for payments of meals and snacks or groceries to entertain visitors/guest in the offices.

