We recommended that management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Issue demand letters to: (i) notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances. If settlement was not received, withhold  from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate; (ii) employees who already resigned and transferred to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Request the write-off of the unliquidated cash advances balance of the dead employees;
Reclassify “Other Receivable” account to Advances to Officers and Employees account in order to present fairly the total balance of unsettled cash advances;
Ensure the completeness of prescribed supporting documents for the granting of cash advances in processing claims for payment thereof; 
Not grant additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advance granted them have been liquidated; 
The Municipal Accountant should not process cash advances of elected officials other than for official travel;
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of the abovementioned Circulars to avoid the penalty stated thereon.

We recommended that Management:
Assess the need to engage in consultancy services;
Justify the contracts of the consultants whose services were only duplication of the functions of regular employees or whose work can be performed by existing plantilla personnel;
In case there is a need for consultants, engage only experts in their respective fields;
Observe rules and regulations on the hiring of consultants; and
Ensure that payments for consultancy services are supported with adequate documentation.

We recommended that Management:
Limit disbursements within the approved budget to avoid incurrence of overdraft.
Formulate guidelines or policies to be adopted in determining the rates or amounts to be granted to identified beneficiaries of financial assistance for an equitable delivery of services and resources to poor, marginalized and vulnerable/disadvantaged individuals;
Beneficiaries/Recipients should be properly screened giving priority to less privileged constituents;
Coordinate with the social welfare department to assess request for medical and/or burial assistance by way of social case study reports so that only deserving indigents are assisted and served;
Stop the practice of reimbursing financial assistance given to various constituents, instead it should be made directly payable to the recipients and duly acknowledge by them; and
Stop the practice of granting financial assistance for Christmas programs, prizes, participation fee in basketball tournament and the like since these are personal in nature and should not be charged to the coffers of the LGU.

We recommended that management:

a] follow up and make appropriate representation with the National Solid Waste Management Commission for the expeditious approval of the municipality’s 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan to ensure compliance with the requirements of RA No. 9003;
b] update the coverage of the SWM Plan to ensure its relevance with current issues in the locality;
c] identify and prioritize programs that comply with environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment; and
d] undertake best practices in adhering to and implementing the provisions of the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000 and its Implementing Rules and Regulations.

We recommended that the concerned office  revisit the existing sales and inventory procedure as well as receipts for hospital services and come up with a solution to address these identified issues:

a] Record all purchases of drugs and medicines to the inventory account and to adjust this account for the consumption on the basis of the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) duly supported with the original copy of Requisition Issue Slip (RIS) as well as sales report which should be prepared by the PGBICH personnel in charge in the disposition of drugs and medicines, to be submitted weekly or monthly to the Municipal Accountant pursuant to Section 121, Volume I of NGAS Manual for LGUs.  This SSMI or the utilization report serves as basis by the accounting and the GSO in determining the actual expenses/utilization/sales for a given period.  Also, maintain perpetual inventory records to be reconciled periodically with the PGBICH records in order to present fairly the actual inventories as well as the expenses in the financial statements;
b] Issue official receipts (AF # 51) on all sales or any payments received;
c] Job order employee should not be assigned to handle cashiering function.

